2099 bool Sema::hasReachableDeclarationSlow(
2100  const NamedDecl *D, llvm::SmallVectorImpl<Module *> *Modules) {
2101  assert(!isReachable(D) && "not in slow case");
2102  return hasAcceptableDeclarationImpl(
2103  *this, D, Modules, [](const NamedDecl *) { return true; },
2104  Sema::AcceptableKind::Reachable);
2105 }
2106 
2107 NamedDecl *LookupResult::getAcceptableDeclSlow(NamedDecl *D) const {
2108  if (auto *ND = dyn_cast<NamespaceDecl>(D)) {
2109  // Namespaces are a bit of a special case: we expect there to be a lot of
2110  // redeclarations of some namespaces, all declarations of a namespace are
2111  // essentially interchangeable, all declarations are found by name lookup
2112  // if any is, and namespaces are never looked up during template
2113  // instantiation. So we benefit from caching the check in this case, and
2114  // it is correct to do so.
2115  auto *Key = ND->getCanonicalDecl();
2116  if (auto *Acceptable = getSema().VisibleNamespaceCache.lookup(Key))
2117  return Acceptable;
2118  auto *Acceptable = isVisible(getSema(), Key)
2119  ? Key
2120  : findAcceptableDecl(getSema(), Key, IDNS);
2121  if (Acceptable)
2122  getSema().VisibleNamespaceCache.insert(std::make_pair(Key, Acceptable));
2123  return Acceptable;
2124  }
2125 
2126  return findAcceptableDecl(getSema(), D, IDNS);
2127 }
2128 
2129 bool LookupResult::isVisible(Sema &SemaRef, NamedDecl *D) {
2130  // If this declaration is already visible, return it directly.
2131  if (D->isUnconditionallyVisible())
2132  return true;
2133 
2134  // During template instantiation, we can refer to hidden declarations, if
2135  // they were visible in any module along the path of instantiation.
2136  return isAcceptableSlow(SemaRef, D, Sema::AcceptableKind::Visible);
2137 }
2138 
2139 bool LookupResult::isReachable(Sema &SemaRef, NamedDecl *D) {
2140  if (D->isUnconditionallyVisible())
2141  return true;
2142 
2143  return isAcceptableSlow(SemaRef, D, Sema::AcceptableKind::Reachable);
2144 }
2145 
2146 bool LookupResult::isAvailableForLookup(Sema &SemaRef, NamedDecl *ND) {
2147  // We should check the visibility at the callsite already.
2148  if (isVisible(SemaRef, ND))
2149  return true;
2150 
2151  // Deduction guide lives in namespace scope generally, but it is just a
2152  // hint to the compilers. What we actually lookup for is the generated member
2153  // of the corresponding template. So it is sufficient to check the
2154  // reachability of the template decl.
2155  if (auto *DeductionGuide = ND->getDeclName().getCXXDeductionGuideTemplate())
2156  return SemaRef.hasReachableDefinition(DeductionGuide);
2157 
2158  // FIXME: The lookup for allocation function is a standalone process.
2159  // (We can find the logics in Sema::FindAllocationFunctions)
2160  //
2161  // Such structure makes it a problem when we instantiate a template
2162  // declaration using placement allocation function if the placement
2163  // allocation function is invisible.
2164  // (See https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/59601)
2165  //
2166  // Here we workaround it by making the placement allocation functions
2167  // always acceptable. The downside is that we can't diagnose the direct
2168  // use of the invisible placement allocation functions. (Although such uses
2169  // should be rare).
2170  if (auto *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(ND);
2171  FD && FD->isReservedGlobalPlacementOperator())
2172  return true;
2173 
2174  auto *DC = ND->getDeclContext();
2175  // If ND is not visible and it is at namespace scope, it shouldn't be found
2176  // by name lookup.
2177  if (DC->isFileContext())
2178  return false;
2179 
2180  // [module.interface]p7
2181  // Class and enumeration member names can be found by name lookup in any
2182  // context in which a definition of the type is reachable.
2183  //
2184  // FIXME: The current implementation didn't consider about scope. For example,
2185  // ```
2186  // // m.cppm
2187  // export module m;
2188  // enum E1 { e1 };
2189  // // Use.cpp
2190  // import m;
2191  // void test() {
2192  // auto a = E1::e1; // Error as expected.
2193  // auto b = e1; // Should be error. namespace-scope name e1 is not visible
2194  // }
2195  // ```
2196  // For the above example, the current implementation would emit error for `a`
2197  // correctly. However, the implementation wouldn't diagnose about `b` now.
2198  // Since we only check the reachability for the parent only.
2199  // See clang/test/CXX/module/module.interface/p7.cpp for example.
2200  if (auto *TD = dyn_cast<TagDecl>(DC))
2201  return SemaRef.hasReachableDefinition(TD);
2202 
2203  return false;
2204 }
2205 
2206 /// Perform unqualified name lookup starting from a given
2207 /// scope.
2208 ///
2209 /// Unqualified name lookup (C++ [basic.lookup.unqual], C99 6.2.1) is
2210 /// used to find names within the current scope. For example, 'x' in
2211 /// @code
2212 /// int x;
2213 /// int f() {
2214 /// return x; // unqualified name look finds 'x' in the global scope
2215 /// }
2216 /// @endcode
2217 ///
2218 /// Different lookup criteria can find different names. For example, a
2219 /// particular scope can have both a struct and a function of the same
2220 /// name, and each can be found by certain lookup criteria. For more
2221 /// information about lookup criteria, see the documentation for the
2222 /// class LookupCriteria.
2223 ///
2224 /// @param S The scope from which unqualified name lookup will
2225 /// begin. If the lookup criteria permits, name lookup may also search
2226 /// in the parent scopes.
2227 ///
2228 /// @param [in,out] R Specifies the lookup to perform (e.g., the name to
2229 /// look up and the lookup kind), and is updated with the results of lookup
2230 /// including zero or more declarations and possibly additional information
2231 /// used to diagnose ambiguities.
2232 ///
2233 /// @returns \c true if lookup succeeded and false otherwise.
2234 bool Sema::LookupName(LookupResult &R, Scope *S, bool AllowBuiltinCreation,
2235  bool ForceNoCPlusPlus) {
2236  DeclarationName Name = R.getLookupName();
2237  if (!Name) return false;
2238 
2239  LookupNameKind NameKind = R.getLookupKind();
2240 
2241  if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus || ForceNoCPlusPlus) {
2242  // Unqualified name lookup in C/Objective-C is purely lexical, so
2243  // search in the declarations attached to the name.
2244  if (NameKind == Sema::LookupRedeclarationWithLinkage) {
2245  // Find the nearest non-transparent declaration scope.
2246  while (!(S->getFlags() & Scope::DeclScope) ||
2247  (S->getEntity() && S->getEntity()->isTransparentContext()))
2248  S = S->getParent();
2249  }
2250 
2251  // When performing a scope lookup, we want to find local extern decls.
2252  FindLocalExternScope FindLocals(R);
2253 
2254  // Scan up the scope chain looking for a decl that matches this
2255  // identifier that is in the appropriate namespace. This search
2256  // should not take long, as shadowing of names is uncommon, and
2257  // deep shadowing is extremely uncommon.
2258  bool LeftStartingScope = false;
2259 
2260  for (IdentifierResolver::iterator I = IdResolver.begin(Name),
2261  IEnd = IdResolver.end();
2262  I != IEnd; ++I)
2263  if (NamedDecl *D = R.getAcceptableDecl(*I)) {
2264  if (NameKind == LookupRedeclarationWithLinkage) {
2265  // Determine whether this (or a previous) declaration is
2266  // out-of-scope.
2267  if (!LeftStartingScope && !S->isDeclScope(*I))
2268  LeftStartingScope = true;
2269 
2270  // If we found something outside of our starting scope that
2271  // does not have linkage, skip it.
2272  if (LeftStartingScope && !((*I)->hasLinkage())) {
2273  R.setShadowed();
2274  continue;
2275  }
2276  }
2277  else if (NameKind == LookupObjCImplicitSelfParam &&
2278  !isa<ImplicitParamDecl>(*I))
2279  continue;
2280 
2281  R.addDecl(D);
2282 
2283  // Check whether there are any other declarations with the same name
2284  // and in the same scope.
2285  if (I != IEnd) {
2286  // Find the scope in which this declaration was declared (if it
2287  // actually exists in a Scope).
2288  while (S && !S->isDeclScope(D))
2289  S = S->getParent();
2290 
2291  // If the scope containing the declaration is the translation unit,
2292  // then we'll need to perform our checks based on the matching
2293  // DeclContexts rather than matching scopes.
2294  if (S && isNamespaceOrTranslationUnitScope(S))
2295  S = nullptr;
2296 
2297  // Compute the DeclContext, if we need it.
2298  DeclContext *DC = nullptr;
2299  if (!S)
2300  DC = (*I)->getDeclContext()->getRedeclContext();
2301 
2302  IdentifierResolver::iterator LastI = I;
2303  for (++LastI; LastI != IEnd; ++LastI) {
2304  if (S) {
2305  // Match based on scope.
2306  if (!S->isDeclScope(*LastI))
2307  break;
2308  } else {
2309  // Match based on DeclContext.
2310  DeclContext *LastDC
2311  = (*LastI)->getDeclContext()->getRedeclContext();
2312  if (!LastDC->Equals(DC))
2313  break;
2314  }
2315 
2316  // If the declaration is in the right namespace and visible, add it.
2317  if (NamedDecl *LastD = R.getAcceptableDecl(*LastI))
2318  R.addDecl(LastD);
2319  }
2320 
2321  R.resolveKind();
2322  }
2323 
2324  return true;
2325  }
2326  } else {
2327  // Perform C++ unqualified name lookup.
2328  if (CppLookupName(R, S))
2329  return true;
2330  }
2331 
2332  // If we didn't find a use of this identifier, and if the identifier
2333  // corresponds to a compiler builtin, create the decl object for the builtin
2334  // now, injecting it into translation unit scope, and return it.
2335  if (AllowBuiltinCreation && LookupBuiltin(R))
2336  return true;
2337 
2338  // If we didn't find a use of this identifier, the ExternalSource
2339  // may be able to handle the situation.
2340  // Note: some lookup failures are expected!
2341  // See e.g. R.isForRedeclaration().
2342  return (ExternalSource && ExternalSource->LookupUnqualified(R, S));
2343 }
2344 
2345 /// Perform qualified name lookup in the namespaces nominated by
2346 /// using directives by the given context.
2347 ///
2348 /// C++98 [namespace.qual]p2:
2349 /// Given X::m (where X is a user-declared namespace), or given \::m
2350 /// (where X is the global namespace), let S be the set of all
2351 /// declarations of m in X and in the transitive closure of all
2352 /// namespaces nominated by using-directives in X and its used
2353 /// namespaces, except that using-directives are ignored in any
2354 /// namespace, including X, directly containing one or more
2355 /// declarations of m. No namespace is searched more than once in
2356 /// the lookup of a name. If S is the empty set, the program is
2357 /// ill-formed. Otherwise, if S has exactly one member, or if the
2358 /// context of the reference is a using-declaration
2359 /// (namespace.udecl), S is the required set of declarations of
2360 /// m. Otherwise if the use of m is not one that allows a unique
2361 /// declaration to be chosen from S, the program is ill-formed.
2362 ///
2363 /// C++98 [namespace.qual]p5:
2364 /// During the lookup of a qualified namespace member name, if the
2365 /// lookup finds more than one declaration of the member, and if one
2366 /// declaration introduces a class name or enumeration name and the
2367 /// other declarations either introduce the same object, the same
2368 /// enumerator or a set of functions, the non-type name hides the
2369 /// class or enumeration name if and only if the declarations are
2370 /// from the same namespace; otherwise (the declarations are from
2371 /// different namespaces), the program is ill-formed.
2372 static bool LookupQualifiedNameInUsingDirectives(Sema &S, LookupResult &R,
2373  DeclContext *StartDC) {
2374  assert(StartDC->isFileContext() && "start context is not a file context");
2375 
2376  // We have not yet looked into these namespaces, much less added
2377  // their "using-children" to the queue.
2378  SmallVector<NamespaceDecl*, 8> Queue;
2379 
2380  // We have at least added all these contexts to the queue.
2381  llvm::SmallPtrSet<DeclContext*, 8> Visited;
2382  Visited.insert(StartDC);
2383 
2384  // We have already looked into the initial namespace; seed the queue
2385  // with its using-children.
2386  for (auto *I : StartDC->using_directives()) {
2387  NamespaceDecl *ND = I->getNominatedNamespace()->getOriginalNamespace();
2388  if (S.isVisible(I) && Visited.insert(ND).second)
2389  Queue.push_back(ND);
2390  }
2391 
2392  // The easiest way to implement the restriction in [namespace.qual]p5
2393  // is to check whether any of the individual results found a tag
2394  // and, if so, to declare an ambiguity if the final result is not
2395  // a tag.
2396  bool FoundTag = false;
2397  bool FoundNonTag = false;
2398 
2399  LookupResult LocalR(LookupResult::Temporary, R);
2400 
2401  bool Found = false;
2402  while (!Queue.empty()) {
2403  NamespaceDecl *ND = Queue.pop_back_val();
2404 
2405  // We go through some convolutions here to avoid copying results
2406  // between LookupResults.
2407  bool UseLocal = !R.empty();
2408  LookupResult &DirectR = UseLocal ? LocalR : R;
2409  bool FoundDirect = LookupDirect(S, DirectR, ND);
2410 
2411  if (FoundDirect) {
2412  // First do any local hiding.
2413  DirectR.resolveKind();
2414 
2415  // If the local result is a tag, remember that.
2416  if (DirectR.isSingleTagDecl())
2417  FoundTag = true;
2418  else
2419  FoundNonTag = true;
2420 
2421  // Append the local results to the total results if necessary.
2422  if (UseLocal) {
2423  R.addAllDecls(LocalR);
2424  LocalR.clear();
2425  }
2426  }
2427 
2428  // If we find names in this namespace, ignore its using directives.
2429  if (FoundDirect) {
2430  Found = true;
2431  continue;
2432  }
2433 
2434  for (auto *I : ND->using_directives()) {
2435  NamespaceDecl *Nom = I->getNominatedNamespace();
2436  if (S.isVisible(I) && Visited.insert(Nom).second)
2437  Queue.push_back(Nom);
2438  }
2439  }
2440 
2441  if (Found) {
2442  if (FoundTag && FoundNonTag)
2443  R.setAmbiguousQualifiedTagHiding();
2444  else
2445  R.resolveKind();
2446  }
2447 
2448  return Found;
2449 }
2450 
2451 /// Perform qualified name lookup into a given context.
2452 ///
2453 /// Qualified name lookup (C++ [basic.lookup.qual]) is used to find
2454 /// names when the context of those names is explicit specified, e.g.,
2455 /// "std::vector" or "x->member", or as part of unqualified name lookup.
2456 ///
2457 /// Different lookup criteria can find different names. For example, a
2458 /// particular scope can have both a struct and a function of the same
2459 /// name, and each can be found by certain lookup criteria. For more
2460 /// information about lookup criteria, see the documentation for the
2461 /// class LookupCriteria.
2462 ///
2463 /// \param R captures both the lookup criteria and any lookup results found.
2464 ///
2465 /// \param LookupCtx The context in which qualified name lookup will
2466 /// search. If the lookup criteria permits, name lookup may also search
2467 /// in the parent contexts or (for C++ classes) base classes.
2468 ///
2469 /// \param InUnqualifiedLookup true if this is qualified name lookup that
2470 /// occurs as part of unqualified name lookup.
2471 ///
2472 /// \returns true if lookup succeeded, false if it failed.
2473 bool Sema::LookupQualifiedName(LookupResult &R, DeclContext *LookupCtx,
2474  bool InUnqualifiedLookup) {
2475  assert(LookupCtx && "Sema::LookupQualifiedName requires a lookup context");
2476 
2477  if (!R.getLookupName())
2478  return false;
2479 
2480  // Make sure that the declaration context is complete.
2481  assert((!isa<TagDecl>(LookupCtx) ||
2482  LookupCtx->isDependentContext() ||
2483  cast<TagDecl>(LookupCtx)->isCompleteDefinition() ||
2484  cast<TagDecl>(LookupCtx)->isBeingDefined()) &&
2485  "Declaration context must already be complete!");
2486 
2487  struct QualifiedLookupInScope {
2488  bool oldVal;
2489  DeclContext *Context;
2490  // Set flag in DeclContext informing debugger that we're looking for qualified name
2491  QualifiedLookupInScope(DeclContext *ctx)
2492  : oldVal(ctx->shouldUseQualifiedLookup()), Context(ctx) {
2493  ctx->setUseQualifiedLookup();
2494  }
2495  ~QualifiedLookupInScope() {
2496  Context->setUseQualifiedLookup(oldVal);
2497  }
2498  } QL(LookupCtx);
2499 
2500  if (LookupDirect(*this, R, LookupCtx)) {
2501  R.resolveKind();
2502  if (isa<CXXRecordDecl>(LookupCtx))
2503  R.setNamingClass(cast<CXXRecordDecl>(LookupCtx));
2504  return true;
2505  }
2506 
2507  // Don't descend into implied contexts for redeclarations.
2508  // C++98 [namespace.qual]p6:
2509  // In a declaration for a namespace member in which the
2510  // declarator-id is a qualified-id, given that the qualified-id
2511  // for the namespace member has the form
2512  // nested-name-specifier unqualified-id
2513  // the unqualified-id shall name a member of the namespace
2514  // designated by the nested-name-specifier.
2515  // See also [class.mfct]p5 and [class.static.data]p2.
2516  if (R.isForRedeclaration())
2517  return false;
2518 
2519  // If this is a namespace, look it up in the implied namespaces.
2520  if (LookupCtx->isFileContext())
2521  return LookupQualifiedNameInUsingDirectives(*this, R, LookupCtx);
2522 
2523  // If this isn't a C++ class, we aren't allowed to look into base
2524  // classes, we're done.
2525  CXXRecordDecl *LookupRec = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(LookupCtx);
2526  if (!LookupRec || !LookupRec->getDefinition())
2527  return false;
2528 
2529  // We're done for lookups that can never succeed for C++ classes.
2530  if (R.getLookupKind() == LookupOperatorName ||
2531  R.getLookupKind() == LookupNamespaceName ||
2532  R.getLookupKind() == LookupObjCProtocolName ||
2533  R.getLookupKind() == LookupLabel)
2534  return false;
2535 
2536  // If we're performing qualified name lookup into a dependent class,
2537  // then we are actually looking into a current instantiation. If we have any
2538  // dependent base classes, then we either have to delay lookup until
2539  // template instantiation time (at which point all bases will be available)
2540  // or we have to fail.
2541  if (!InUnqualifiedLookup && LookupRec->isDependentContext() &&
2542  LookupRec->hasAnyDependentBases()) {
2543  R.setNotFoundInCurrentInstantiation();
2544  return false;
2545  }
2546 
2547  // Perform lookup into our base classes.
2548 
2549  DeclarationName Name = R.getLookupName();
2550  unsigned IDNS = R.getIdentifierNamespace();
2551 
2552  // Look for this member in our base classes.
2553  auto BaseCallback = [Name, IDNS](const CXXBaseSpecifier *Specifier,
2554  CXXBasePath &Path) -> bool {
2555  CXXRecordDecl *BaseRecord = Specifier->getType()->getAsCXXRecordDecl();
2556  // Drop leading non-matching lookup results from the declaration list so
2557  // we don't need to consider them again below.
2558  for (Path.Decls = BaseRecord->lookup(Name).begin();
2559  Path.Decls != Path.Decls.end(); ++Path.Decls) {
2560  if ((*Path.Decls)->isInIdentifierNamespace(IDNS))
2561  return true;
2562  }
2563  return false;
2564  };
2565 
2566  CXXBasePaths Paths;
2567  Paths.setOrigin(LookupRec);
2568  if (!LookupRec->lookupInBases(BaseCallback, Paths))
2569  return false;
2570 
2571  R.setNamingClass(LookupRec);
2572 
2573  // C++ [class.member.lookup]p2:
2574  // [...] If the resulting set of declarations are not all from
2575  // sub-objects of the same type, or the set has a nonstatic member
2576  // and includes members from distinct sub-objects, there is an
2577  // ambiguity and the program is ill-formed. Otherwise that set is
2578  // the result of the lookup.
2579  QualType SubobjectType;
2580  int SubobjectNumber = 0;
2581  AccessSpecifier SubobjectAccess = AS_none;
2582 
2583  // Check whether the given lookup result contains only static members.
2584  auto HasOnlyStaticMembers = [&](DeclContext::lookup_iterator Result) {
2585  for (DeclContext::lookup_iterator I = Result, E = I.end(); I != E; ++I)
2586  if ((*I)->isInIdentifierNamespace(IDNS) && (*I)->isCXXInstanceMember())
2587  return false;
2588  return true;
2589  };
2590 
2591  bool TemplateNameLookup = R.isTemplateNameLookup();
2592 
2593  // Determine whether two sets of members contain the same members, as
2594  // required by C++ [class.member.lookup]p6.
2595  auto HasSameDeclarations = [&](DeclContext::lookup_iterator A,
2596  DeclContext::lookup_iterator B) {
2597  using Iterator = DeclContextLookupResult::iterator;
2598  using Result = const void *;
2599 
2600  auto Next = [&](Iterator &It, Iterator End) -> Result {
2601  while (It != End) {
2602  NamedDecl *ND = *It++;
2603  if (!ND->isInIdentifierNamespace(IDNS))
2604  continue;
2605 
2606  // C++ [temp.local]p3:
2607  // A lookup that finds an injected-class-name (10.2) can result in
2608  // an ambiguity in certain cases (for example, if it is found in
2609  // more than one base class). If all of the injected-class-names
2610  // that are found refer to specializations of the same class
2611  // template, and if the name is used as a template-name, the
2612  // reference refers to the class template itself and not a
2613  // specialization thereof, and is not ambiguous.
2614  if (TemplateNameLookup)
2615  if (auto *TD = getAsTemplateNameDecl(ND))
2616  ND = TD;
2617 
2618  // C++ [class.member.lookup]p3:
2619  // type declarations (including injected-class-names) are replaced by
2620  // the types they designate
2621  if (const TypeDecl *TD = dyn_cast<TypeDecl>(ND->getUnderlyingDecl())) {
2622  QualType T = Context.getTypeDeclType(TD);
2623  return T.getCanonicalType().getAsOpaquePtr();
2624  }
2625 
2626  return ND->getUnderlyingDecl()->getCanonicalDecl();
2627  }
2628  return nullptr;
2629  };
2630 
2631  // We'll often find the declarations are in the same order. Handle this
2632  // case (and the special case of only one declaration) efficiently.
2633  Iterator AIt = A, BIt = B, AEnd, BEnd;
2634  while (true) {
2635  Result AResult = Next(AIt, AEnd);
2636  Result BResult = Next(BIt, BEnd);
2637  if (!AResult && !BResult)
2638  return true;
2639  if (!AResult || !BResult)
2640  return false;
2641  if (AResult != BResult) {
2642  // Found a mismatch; carefully check both lists, accounting for the
2643  // possibility of declarations appearing more than once.
2644  llvm::SmallDenseMap<Result, bool, 32> AResults;
2645  for (; AResult; AResult = Next(AIt, AEnd))
2646  AResults.insert({AResult, /*FoundInB*/false});
2647  unsigned Found = 0;
2648  for (; BResult; BResult = Next(BIt, BEnd)) {
2649  auto It = AResults.find(BResult);
2650  if (It == AResults.end())
2651  return false;
2652  if (!It->second) {
2653  It->second = true;
2654  ++Found;
2655  }
2656  }
2657  return AResults.size() == Found;
2658  }
2659  }
2660  };
2661 
2662  for (CXXBasePaths::paths_iterator Path = Paths.begin(), PathEnd = Paths.end();
2663  Path != PathEnd; ++Path) {
2664  const CXXBasePathElement &PathElement = Path->back();
2665 
2666  // Pick the best (i.e. most permissive i.e. numerically lowest) access
2667  // across all paths.
2668  SubobjectAccess = std::min(SubobjectAccess, Path->Access);
2669 
2670  // Determine whether we're looking at a distinct sub-object or not.
2671  if (SubobjectType.isNull()) {
2672  // This is the first subobject we've looked at. Record its type.
2673  SubobjectType = Context.getCanonicalType(PathElement.Base->getType());
2674  SubobjectNumber = PathElement.SubobjectNumber;
2675  continue;
2676  }
2677 
2678  if (SubobjectType !=
2679  Context.getCanonicalType(PathElement.Base->getType())) {
2680  // We found members of the given name in two subobjects of
2681  // different types. If the declaration sets aren't the same, this
2682  // lookup is ambiguous.
2683  //
2684  // FIXME: The language rule says that this applies irrespective of
2685  // whether the sets contain only static members.
2686  if (HasOnlyStaticMembers(Path->Decls) &&
2687  HasSameDeclarations(Paths.begin()->Decls, Path->Decls))
2688  continue;
2689 
2690  R.setAmbiguousBaseSubobjectTypes(Paths);
2691  return true;
2692  }
2693 
2694  // FIXME: This language rule no longer exists. Checking for ambiguous base
2695  // subobjects should be done as part of formation of a class member access
2696  // expression (when converting the object parameter to the member's type).
2697  if (SubobjectNumber != PathElement.SubobjectNumber) {
2698  // We have a different subobject of the same type.
2699 
2700  // C++ [class.member.lookup]p5:
2701  // A static member, a nested type or an enumerator defined in
2702  // a base class T can unambiguously be found even if an object
2703  // has more than one base class subobject of type T.
2704  if (HasOnlyStaticMembers(Path->Decls))
2705  continue;
2706 
2707  // We have found a nonstatic member name in multiple, distinct
2708  // subobjects. Name lookup is ambiguous.
2709  R.setAmbiguousBaseSubobjects(Paths);
2710  return true;
2711  }
2712  }
2713 
2714  // Lookup in a base class succeeded; return these results.
2715 
2716  for (DeclContext::lookup_iterator I = Paths.front().Decls, E = I.end();
2717  I != E; ++I) {
2718  AccessSpecifier AS = CXXRecordDecl::MergeAccess(SubobjectAccess,
2719  (*I)->getAccess());
2720  if (NamedDecl *ND = R.getAcceptableDecl(*I))
2721  R.addDecl(ND, AS);
2722  }
2723  R.resolveKind();
2724  return true;
2725 }
2726 
2727 /// Performs qualified name lookup or special type of lookup for
2728 /// "__super::" scope specifier.
2729 ///
2730 /// This routine is a convenience overload meant to be called from contexts
2731 /// that need to perform a qualified name lookup with an optional C++ scope
2732 /// specifier that might require special kind of lookup.
2733 ///
2734 /// \param R captures both the lookup criteria and any lookup results found.
2735 ///
2736 /// \param LookupCtx The context in which qualified name lookup will
2737 /// search.
2738 ///
2739 /// \param SS An optional C++ scope-specifier.
2740 ///
2741 /// \returns true if lookup succeeded, false if it failed.
2742 bool Sema::LookupQualifiedName(LookupResult &R, DeclContext *LookupCtx,
2743  CXXScopeSpec &SS) {
2744  auto *NNS = SS.getScopeRep();
2745  if (NNS && NNS->getKind() == NestedNameSpecifier::Super)
2746  return LookupInSuper(R, NNS->getAsRecordDecl());
2747  else
2748 
2749  return LookupQualifiedName(R, LookupCtx);
2750 }
2751 
2752 /// Performs name lookup for a name that was parsed in the
2753 /// source code, and may contain a C++ scope specifier.
2754 ///
2755 /// This routine is a convenience routine meant to be called from
2756 /// contexts that receive a name and an optional C++ scope specifier
2757 /// (e.g., "N::M::x"). It will then perform either qualified or
2758 /// unqualified name lookup (with LookupQualifiedName or LookupName,
2759 /// respectively) on the given name and return those results. It will
2760 /// perform a special type of lookup for "__super::" scope specifier.
2761 ///
2762 /// @param S The scope from which unqualified name lookup will
2763 /// begin.
2764 ///
2765 /// @param SS An optional C++ scope-specifier, e.g., "::N::M".
2766 ///
2767 /// @param EnteringContext Indicates whether we are going to enter the
2768 /// context of the scope-specifier SS (if present).
2769 ///
2770 /// @returns True if any decls were found (but possibly ambiguous)
2771 bool Sema::LookupParsedName(LookupResult &R, Scope *S, CXXScopeSpec *SS,
2772  bool AllowBuiltinCreation, bool EnteringContext) {
2773  if (SS && SS->isInvalid()) {
2774  // When the scope specifier is invalid, don't even look for
2775  // anything.
2776  return false;
2777  }
2778 
2779  if (SS && SS->isSet()) {
2780  NestedNameSpecifier *NNS = SS->getScopeRep();
2781  if (NNS->getKind() == NestedNameSpecifier::Super)
2782  return LookupInSuper(R, NNS->getAsRecordDecl());
2783 
2784  if (DeclContext *DC = computeDeclContext(*SS, EnteringContext)) {
2785  // We have resolved the scope specifier to a particular declaration
2786  // contex, and will perform name lookup in that context.
2787  if (!DC->isDependentContext() && RequireCompleteDeclContext(*SS, DC))
2788  return false;
2789 
2790  R.setContextRange(SS->getRange());
2791  return LookupQualifiedName(R, DC);
2792  }
2793 
2794  // We could not resolve the scope specified to a specific declaration
2795  // context, which means that SS refers to an unknown specialization.
2796  // Name lookup can't find anything in this case.
2797  R.setNotFoundInCurrentInstantiation();
2798  R.setContextRange(SS->getRange());
2799  return false;
2800  }
2801 
2802  // Perform unqualified name lookup starting in the given scope.
2803  return LookupName(R, S, AllowBuiltinCreation);
2804 }
2805 
2806 /// Perform qualified name lookup into all base classes of the given
2807 /// class.
2808 ///
2809 /// \param R captures both the lookup criteria and any lookup results found.
2810 ///
2811 /// \param Class The context in which qualified name lookup will
2812 /// search. Name lookup will search in all base classes merging the results.
2813 ///
2814 /// @returns True if any decls were found (but possibly ambiguous)
2815 bool Sema::LookupInSuper(LookupResult &R, CXXRecordDecl *Class) {
2816  // The access-control rules we use here are essentially the rules for
2817  // doing a lookup in Class that just magically skipped the direct
2818  // members of Class itself. That is, the naming class is Class, and the
2819  // access includes the access of the base.
2820  for (const auto &BaseSpec : Class->bases()) {
2821  CXXRecordDecl *RD = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(
2822  BaseSpec.getType()->castAs<RecordType>()->getDecl());
2823  LookupResult Result(*this, R.getLookupNameInfo(), R.getLookupKind());
2824  Result.setBaseObjectType(Context.getRecordType(Class));
2825  LookupQualifiedName(Result, RD);
2826 
2827  // Copy the lookup results into the target, merging the base's access into
2828  // the path access.
2829  for (auto I = Result.begin(), E = Result.end(); I != E; ++I) {
2830  R.addDecl(I.getDecl(),
2831  CXXRecordDecl::MergeAccess(BaseSpec.getAccessSpecifier(),
2832  I.getAccess()));
2833  }
2834 
2835  Result.suppressDiagnostics();
2836  }
2837 
2838  R.resolveKind();
2839  R.setNamingClass(Class);
2840 
2841  return !R.empty();
2842 }
2843 
2844 /// Produce a diagnostic describing the ambiguity that resulted
2845 /// from name lookup.
2846 ///
2847 /// \param Result The result of the ambiguous lookup to be diagnosed.
2848 void Sema::DiagnoseAmbiguousLookup(LookupResult &Result) {
2849  assert(Result.isAmbiguous() && "Lookup result must be ambiguous");
2850 
2851  DeclarationName Name = Result.getLookupName();
2852  SourceLocation NameLoc = Result.getNameLoc();
2853  SourceRange LookupRange = Result.getContextRange();
2854 
2855  switch (Result.getAmbiguityKind()) {
2856  case LookupResult::AmbiguousBaseSubobjects: {
2857  CXXBasePaths *Paths = Result.getBasePaths();
2858  QualType SubobjectType = Paths->front().back().Base->getType();
2859  Diag(NameLoc, diag::err_ambiguous_member_multiple_subobjects)
2860  << Name << SubobjectType << getAmbiguousPathsDisplayString(*Paths)
2861  << LookupRange;
2862 
2863  DeclContext::lookup_iterator Found = Paths->front().Decls;
2864  while (isa<CXXMethodDecl>(*Found) &&
2865  cast<CXXMethodDecl>(*Found)->isStatic())
2866  ++Found;
2867 
2868  Diag((*Found)->getLocation(), diag::note_ambiguous_member_found);
2869  break;
2870  }
2871 
2872  case LookupResult::AmbiguousBaseSubobjectTypes: {
2873  Diag(NameLoc, diag::err_ambiguous_member_multiple_subobject_types)
2874  << Name << LookupRange;
2875 
2876  CXXBasePaths *Paths = Result.getBasePaths();
2877  std::set<const NamedDecl *> DeclsPrinted;
2878  for (CXXBasePaths::paths_iterator Path = Paths->begin(),
2879  PathEnd = Paths->end();
2880  Path != PathEnd; ++Path) {
2881  const NamedDecl *D = *Path->Decls;
2882  if (!D->isInIdentifierNamespace(Result.getIdentifierNamespace()))
2883  continue;
2884  if (DeclsPrinted.insert(D).second) {
2885  if (const auto *TD = dyn_cast<TypedefNameDecl>(D->getUnderlyingDecl()))
2886  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_ambiguous_member_type_found)
2887  << TD->getUnderlyingType();
2888  else if (const auto *TD = dyn_cast<TypeDecl>(D->getUnderlyingDecl()))
2889  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_ambiguous_member_type_found)
2890  << Context.getTypeDeclType(TD);
2891  else
2892  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_ambiguous_member_found);
2893  }
2894  }
2895  break;
2896  }
2897 
2898  case LookupResult::AmbiguousTagHiding: {
2899  Diag(NameLoc, diag::err_ambiguous_tag_hiding) << Name << LookupRange;
2900 
2901  llvm::SmallPtrSet<NamedDecl*, 8> TagDecls;
2902 
2903  for (auto *D : Result)
2904  if (TagDecl *TD = dyn_cast<TagDecl>(D)) {
2905  TagDecls.insert(TD);
2906  Diag(TD->getLocation(), diag::note_hidden_tag);
2907  }
2908 
2909  for (auto *D : Result)
2910  if (!isa<TagDecl>(D))
2911  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_hiding_object);
2912 
2913  // For recovery purposes, go ahead and implement the hiding.
2914  LookupResult::Filter F = Result.makeFilter();
2915  while (F.hasNext()) {
2916  if (TagDecls.count(F.next()))
2917  F.erase();
2918  }
2919  F.done();
2920  break;
2921  }
2922 
2923  case LookupResult::AmbiguousReferenceToPlaceholderVariable: {
2924  Diag(NameLoc, diag::err_using_placeholder_variable) << Name << LookupRange;
2925  DeclContext *DC = nullptr;
2926  for (auto *D : Result) {
2927  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_reference_placeholder) << D;
2928  if (DC != nullptr && DC != D->getDeclContext())
2929  break;
2930  DC = D->getDeclContext();
2931  }
2932  break;
2933  }
2934 
2935  case LookupResult::AmbiguousReference: {
2936  Diag(NameLoc, diag::err_ambiguous_reference) << Name << LookupRange;
2937 
2938  for (auto *D : Result)
2939  Diag(D->getLocation(), diag::note_ambiguous_candidate) << D;
2940  break;
2941  }
2942  }
2943 }

2945 namespace {
2946  struct AssociatedLookup {
2947  AssociatedLookup(Sema &S, SourceLocation InstantiationLoc,
2948  Sema::AssociatedNamespaceSet &Namespaces,
2949  Sema::AssociatedClassSet &Classes)
2950  : S(S), Namespaces(Namespaces), Classes(Classes),
2951  InstantiationLoc(InstantiationLoc) {
2952  }
2953 
2954  bool addClassTransitive(CXXRecordDecl *RD) {
2955  Classes.insert(RD);
2956  return ClassesTransitive.insert(RD);
2957  }
2958 
2959  Sema &S;
2960  Sema::AssociatedNamespaceSet &Namespaces;
2961  Sema::AssociatedClassSet &Classes;
2962  SourceLocation InstantiationLoc;
2963 
2964  private:
2965  Sema::AssociatedClassSet ClassesTransitive;
2966  };
2967 } // end anonymous namespace
2968 
2969 static void
2970 addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(AssociatedLookup &Result, QualType T);
2971 
2972 // Given the declaration context \param Ctx of a class, class template or
2973 // enumeration, add the associated namespaces to \param Namespaces as described
2974 // in [basic.lookup.argdep]p2.
2975 static void CollectEnclosingNamespace(Sema::AssociatedNamespaceSet &Namespaces,
2976  DeclContext *Ctx) {
2977  // The exact wording has been changed in C++14 as a result of
2978  // CWG 1691 (see also CWG 1690 and CWG 1692). We apply it unconditionally
2979  // to all language versions since it is possible to return a local type
2980  // from a lambda in C++11.
2981  //
2982  // C++14 [basic.lookup.argdep]p2:
2983  // If T is a class type [...]. Its associated namespaces are the innermost
2984  // enclosing namespaces of its associated classes. [...]
2985  //
2986  // If T is an enumeration type, its associated namespace is the innermost
2987  // enclosing namespace of its declaration. [...]
2988 
2989  // We additionally skip inline namespaces. The innermost non-inline namespace
2990  // contains all names of all its nested inline namespaces anyway, so we can
2991  // replace the entire inline namespace tree with its root.
2992  while (!Ctx->isFileContext() || Ctx->isInlineNamespace())
2993  Ctx = Ctx->getParent();
2994 
2995  Namespaces.insert(Ctx->getPrimaryContext());
2996 }
2997 
2998 // Add the associated classes and namespaces for argument-dependent
2999 // lookup that involves a template argument (C++ [basic.lookup.argdep]p2).
3000 static void
3001 addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(AssociatedLookup &Result,
3002  const TemplateArgument &Arg) {
3003  // C++ [basic.lookup.argdep]p2, last bullet:
3004  // -- [...] ;
3005  switch (Arg.getKind()) {
3006  case TemplateArgument::Null:
3007  break;
3008 
3009  case TemplateArgument::Type:
3010  // [...] the namespaces and classes associated with the types of the
3011  // template arguments provided for template type parameters (excluding
3012  // template template parameters)
3013  addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Result, Arg.getAsType());
3014  break;
3015 
3016  case TemplateArgument::Template:
3017  case TemplateArgument::TemplateExpansion: {
3018  // [...] the namespaces in which any template template arguments are
3019  // defined; and the classes in which any member templates used as
3020  // template template arguments are defined.
3021  TemplateName Template = Arg.getAsTemplateOrTemplatePattern();
3022  if (ClassTemplateDecl *ClassTemplate
3023  = dyn_cast<ClassTemplateDecl>(Template.getAsTemplateDecl())) {
3024  DeclContext *Ctx = ClassTemplate->getDeclContext();
3025  if (CXXRecordDecl *EnclosingClass = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Ctx))
3026  Result.Classes.insert(EnclosingClass);
3027  // Add the associated namespace for this class.
3028  CollectEnclosingNamespace(Result.Namespaces, Ctx);
3029  }
3030  break;
3031  }
3032 
3033  case TemplateArgument::Declaration:
3034  case TemplateArgument::Integral:
3035  case TemplateArgument::Expression:
3036  case TemplateArgument::NullPtr:
3037  case TemplateArgument::StructuralValue:
3038  // [Note: non-type template arguments do not contribute to the set of
3039  // associated namespaces. ]
3040  break;
3041 
3042  case TemplateArgument::Pack:
3043  for (const auto &P : Arg.pack_elements())
3044  addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Result, P);
3045  break;
3046  }
3047 }
3048 
3049 // Add the associated classes and namespaces for argument-dependent lookup
3050 // with an argument of class type (C++ [basic.lookup.argdep]p2).
3051 static void
3052 addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(AssociatedLookup &Result,
3053  CXXRecordDecl *Class) {
3054 
3055  // Just silently ignore anything whose name is __va_list_tag.
3056  if (Class->getDeclName() == Result.S.VAListTagName)
3057  return;
3058 
3059  // C++ [basic.lookup.argdep]p2:
3060  // [...]
3061  // -- If T is a class type (including unions), its associated
3062  // classes are: the class itself; the class of which it is a
3063  // member, if any; and its direct and indirect base classes.
3064  // Its associated namespaces are the innermost enclosing
3065  // namespaces of its associated classes.
3066 
3067  // Add the class of which it is a member, if any.
3068  DeclContext *Ctx = Class->getDeclContext();
3069  if (CXXRecordDecl *EnclosingClass = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Ctx))
3070  Result.Classes.insert(EnclosingClass);
3071 
3072  // Add the associated namespace for this class.
3073  CollectEnclosingNamespace(Result.Namespaces, Ctx);
3074 
3075  // -- If T is a template-id, its associated namespaces and classes are
3076  // the namespace in which the template is defined; for member
3077  // templates, the member template's class; the namespaces and classes
3078  // associated with the types of the template arguments provided for
3079  // template type parameters (excluding template template parameters); the
3080  // namespaces in which any template template arguments are defined; and
3081  // the classes in which any member templates used as template template
3082  // arguments are defined. [Note: non-type template arguments do not
3083  // contribute to the set of associated namespaces. ]
3084  if (ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl *Spec
3085  = dyn_cast<ClassTemplateSpecializationDecl>(Class)) {
3086  DeclContext *Ctx = Spec->getSpecializedTemplate()->getDeclContext();
3087  if (CXXRecordDecl *EnclosingClass = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Ctx))
3088  Result.Classes.insert(EnclosingClass);
3089  // Add the associated namespace for this class.
3090  CollectEnclosingNamespace(Result.Namespaces, Ctx);
3091 
3092  const TemplateArgumentList &TemplateArgs = Spec->getTemplateArgs();
3093  for (unsigned I = 0, N = TemplateArgs.size(); I != N; ++I)
3094  addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Result, TemplateArgs[I]);
3095  }
3096 
3097  // Add the class itself. If we've already transitively visited this class,
3098  // we don't need to visit base classes.
3099  if (!Result.addClassTransitive(Class))
3100  return;
3101 
3102  // Only recurse into base classes for complete types.
3103  if (!Result.S.isCompleteType(Result.InstantiationLoc,
3104  Result.S.Context.getRecordType(Class)))
3105  return;
3106 
3107  // Add direct and indirect base classes along with their associated
3108  // namespaces.
3109  SmallVector<CXXRecordDecl *, 32> Bases;
3110  Bases.push_back(Class);
3111  while (!Bases.empty()) {
3112  // Pop this class off the stack.
3113  Class = Bases.pop_back_val();
3114 
3115  // Visit the base classes.
3116  for (const auto &Base : Class->bases()) {
3117  const RecordType *BaseType = Base.getType()->getAs<RecordType>();
3118  // In dependent contexts, we do ADL twice, and the first time around,
3119  // the base type might be a dependent TemplateSpecializationType, or a
3120  // TemplateTypeParmType. If that happens, simply ignore it.
3121  // FIXME: If we want to support export, we probably need to add the
3122  // namespace of the template in a TemplateSpecializationType, or even
3123  // the classes and namespaces of known non-dependent arguments.
3124  if (!BaseType)
3125  continue;
3126  CXXRecordDecl *BaseDecl = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(BaseType->getDecl());
3127  if (Result.addClassTransitive(BaseDecl)) {
3128  // Find the associated namespace for this base class.
3129  DeclContext *BaseCtx = BaseDecl->getDeclContext();
3130  CollectEnclosingNamespace(Result.Namespaces, BaseCtx);
3131 
3132  // Make sure we visit the bases of this base class.
3133  if (BaseDecl->bases_begin() != BaseDecl->bases_end())
3134  Bases.push_back(BaseDecl);
3135  }
3136  }
3137  }
3138 }
3139 
3140 // Add the associated classes and namespaces for
3141 // argument-dependent lookup with an argument of type T
3142 // (C++ [basic.lookup.koenig]p2).
3143 static void
3144 addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(AssociatedLookup &Result, QualType Ty) {
3145  // C++ [basic.lookup.koenig]p2:
3146  //
3147  // For each argument type T in the function call, there is a set
3148  // of zero or more associated namespaces and a set of zero or more
3149  // associated classes to be considered. The sets of namespaces and
3150  // classes is determined entirely by the types of the function
3151  // arguments (and the namespace of any template template
3152  // argument). Typedef names and using-declarations used to specify
3153  // the types do not contribute to this set. The sets of namespaces
3154  // and classes are determined in the following way:
3155 
3156  SmallVector<const Type *, 16> Queue;
3157  const Type *T = Ty->getCanonicalTypeInternal().getTypePtr();
3158 
3159  while (true) {
3160  switch (T->getTypeClass()) {
3161 
3162 #define TYPE(Class, Base)
3163 #define DEPENDENT_TYPE(Class, Base) case Type::Class:
3164 #define NON_CANONICAL_TYPE(Class, Base) case Type::Class:
3165 #define NON_CANONICAL_UNLESS_DEPENDENT_TYPE(Class, Base) case Type::Class:
3166 #define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Base)
3167 #include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.inc"
3168  // T is canonical. We can also ignore dependent types because
3169  // we don't need to do ADL at the definition point, but if we
3170  // wanted to implement template export (or if we find some other
3171  // use for associated classes and namespaces...) this would be
3172  // wrong.
3173  break;
3174 
3175  // -- If T is a pointer to U or an array of U, its associated
3176  // namespaces and classes are those associated with U.
3177  case Type::Pointer:
3178  T = cast<PointerType>(T)->getPointeeType().getTypePtr();
3179  continue;
3180  case Type::ConstantArray:
3181  case Type::IncompleteArray:
3182  case Type::VariableArray:
3183  T = cast<ArrayType>(T)->getElementType().getTypePtr();
3184  continue;
3185 
3186  // -- If T is a fundamental type, its associated sets of
3187  // namespaces and classes are both empty.
3188  case Type::Builtin:
3189  break;
3190 
3191  // -- If T is a class type (including unions), its associated
3192  // classes are: the class itself; the class of which it is
3193  // a member, if any; and its direct and indirect base classes.
3194  // Its associated namespaces are the innermost enclosing
3195  // namespaces of its associated classes.
3196  case Type::Record: {
3197  CXXRecordDecl *Class =
3198  cast<CXXRecordDecl>(cast<RecordType>(T)->getDecl());
3199  addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Result, Class);
3200  break;
3201  }
3202 
3203  // -- If T is an enumeration type, its associated namespace
3204  // is the innermost enclosing namespace of its declaration.
3205  // If it is a class member, its associated class is the
3206  // members class; else it has no associated class.
3207  case Type::Enum: {
3208  EnumDecl *Enum = cast<EnumType>(T)->getDecl();
3209 
3210  DeclContext *Ctx = Enum->getDeclContext();
3211  if (CXXRecordDecl *EnclosingClass = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(Ctx))
3212  Result.Classes.insert(EnclosingClass);
3213 
3214  // Add the associated namespace for this enumeration.
3215  CollectEnclosingNamespace(Result.Namespaces, Ctx);
3216 
3217  break;
3218  }
3219 
3220  // -- If T is a function type, its associated namespaces and
3221  // classes are those associated with the function parameter
3222  // types and those associated with the return type.
3223  case Type::FunctionProto: {
3224  const FunctionProtoType *Proto = cast<FunctionProtoType>(T);
3225  for (const auto &Arg : Proto->param_types())
3226  Queue.push_back(Arg.getTypePtr());
3227  // fallthrough
3228  [[fallthrough]];
3229  }
3230  case Type::FunctionNoProto: {
3231  const FunctionType *FnType = cast<FunctionType>(T);
3232  T = FnType->getReturnType().getTypePtr();
3233  continue;
3234  }
3235 
3236  // -- If T is a pointer to a member function of a class X, its
3237  // associated namespaces and classes are those associated
3238  // with the function parameter types and return type,
3239  // together with those associated with X.
3240  //
3241  // -- If T is a pointer to a data member of class X, its
3242  // associated namespaces and classes are those associated
3243  // with the member type together with those associated with
3244  // X.
3245  case Type::MemberPointer: {
3246  const MemberPointerType *MemberPtr = cast<MemberPointerType>(T);
3247 
3248  // Queue up the class type into which this points.
3249  Queue.push_back(MemberPtr->getClass());
3250 
3251  // And directly continue with the pointee type.
3252  T = MemberPtr->getPointeeType().getTypePtr();
3253  continue;
3254  }
3255 
3256  // As an extension, treat this like a normal pointer.
3257  case Type::BlockPointer:
3258  T = cast<BlockPointerType>(T)->getPointeeType().getTypePtr();
3259  continue;
3260 
3261  // References aren't covered by the standard, but that's such an
3262  // obvious defect that we cover them anyway.
3263  case Type::LValueReference:
3264  case Type::RValueReference:
3265  T = cast<ReferenceType>(T)->getPointeeType().getTypePtr();
3266  continue;
3267 
3268  // These are fundamental types.
3269  case Type::Vector:
3270  case Type::ExtVector:
3271  case Type::ConstantMatrix:
3272  case Type::Complex:
3273  case Type::BitInt:
3274  break;
3275 
3276  // Non-deduced auto types only get here for error cases.
3277  case Type::Auto:
3278  case Type::DeducedTemplateSpecialization:
3279  break;
3280 
3281  // If T is an Objective-C object or interface type, or a pointer to an
3282  // object or interface type, the associated namespace is the global
3283  // namespace.
3284  case Type::ObjCObject:
3285  case Type::ObjCInterface:
3286  case Type::ObjCObjectPointer:
3287  Result.Namespaces.insert(Result.S.Context.getTranslationUnitDecl());
3288  break;
3289 
3290  // Atomic types are just wrappers; use the associations of the
3291  // contained type.
3292  case Type::Atomic:
3293  T = cast<AtomicType>(T)->getValueType().getTypePtr();
3294  continue;
3295  case Type::Pipe:
3296  T = cast<PipeType>(T)->getElementType().getTypePtr();
3297  continue;
3298 
3299  // Array parameter types are treated as fundamental types.
3300  case Type::ArrayParameter:
3301  break;
3302  }
3303 
3304  if (Queue.empty())
3305  break;
3306  T = Queue.pop_back_val();
3307  }
3308 }
3309 
3310 /// Find the associated classes and namespaces for
3311 /// argument-dependent lookup for a call with the given set of
3312 /// arguments.
3313 ///
3314 /// This routine computes the sets of associated classes and associated
3315 /// namespaces searched by argument-dependent lookup
3316 /// (C++ [basic.lookup.argdep]) for a given set of arguments.
3317 void Sema::FindAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(
3318  SourceLocation InstantiationLoc, ArrayRef<Expr *> Args,
3319  AssociatedNamespaceSet &AssociatedNamespaces,
3320  AssociatedClassSet &AssociatedClasses) {
3321  AssociatedNamespaces.clear();
3322  AssociatedClasses.clear();
3323 
3324  AssociatedLookup Result(*this, InstantiationLoc,
3325  AssociatedNamespaces, AssociatedClasses);
3326 
3327  // C++ [basic.lookup.koenig]p2:
3328  // For each argument type T in the function call, there is a set
3329  // of zero or more associated namespaces and a set of zero or more
3330  // associated classes to be considered. The sets of namespaces and
3331  // classes is determined entirely by the types of the function
3332  // arguments (and the namespace of any template template
3333  // argument).
3334  for (unsigned ArgIdx = 0; ArgIdx != Args.size(); ++ArgIdx) {
3335  Expr *Arg = Args[ArgIdx];
3336 
3337  if (Arg->getType() != Context.OverloadTy) {
3338  addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Result, Arg->getType());
3339  continue;
3340  }
3341 
3342  // [...] In addition, if the argument is the name or address of a
3343  // set of overloaded functions and/or function templates, its
3344  // associated classes and namespaces are the union of those
3345  // associated with each of the members of the set: the namespace
3346  // in which the function or function template is defined and the
3347  // classes and namespaces associated with its (non-dependent)
3348  // parameter types and return type.
3349  OverloadExpr *OE = OverloadExpr::find(Arg).Expression;
3350 
3351  for (const NamedDecl *D : OE->decls()) {
3352  // Look through any using declarations to find the underlying function.
3353  const FunctionDecl *FDecl = D->getUnderlyingDecl()->getAsFunction();
3354 
3355  // Add the classes and namespaces associated with the parameter
3356  // types and return type of this function.
3357  addAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Result, FDecl->getType());
3358  }
3359  }
3360 }
3361 
3362 NamedDecl *Sema::LookupSingleName(Scope *S, DeclarationName Name,
3363  SourceLocation Loc,
3364  LookupNameKind NameKind,
3365  RedeclarationKind Redecl) {
3366  LookupResult R(*this, Name, Loc, NameKind, Redecl);
3367  LookupName(R, S);
3368  return R.getAsSingle<NamedDecl>();
3369 }

3371 /// Find the protocol with the given name, if any.
3372 ObjCProtocolDecl *Sema::LookupProtocol(IdentifierInfo *II,
3373  SourceLocation IdLoc,
3374  RedeclarationKind Redecl) {
3375  Decl *D = LookupSingleName(TUScope, II, IdLoc,
3376  LookupObjCProtocolName, Redecl);
3377  return cast_or_null<ObjCProtocolDecl>(D);
3378 }
3379 
3380 void Sema::LookupOverloadedOperatorName(OverloadedOperatorKind Op, Scope *S,
3381  UnresolvedSetImpl &Functions) {
3382  // C++ [over.match.oper]p3:
3383  // -- The set of non-member candidates is the result of the
3384  // unqualified lookup of operator@ in the context of the
3385  // expression according to the usual rules for name lookup in
3386  // unqualified function calls (3.4.2) except that all member
3387  // functions are ignored.
3388  DeclarationName OpName = Context.DeclarationNames.getCXXOperatorName(Op);
3389  LookupResult Operators(*this, OpName, SourceLocation(), LookupOperatorName);
3390  LookupName(Operators, S);
3391 
3392  assert(!Operators.isAmbiguous() && "Operator lookup cannot be ambiguous");
3393  Functions.append(Operators.begin(), Operators.end());
3394 }
3395 
3396 Sema::SpecialMemberOverloadResult
3397 Sema::LookupSpecialMember(CXXRecordDecl *RD, CXXSpecialMemberKind SM,
3398  bool ConstArg, bool VolatileArg, bool RValueThis,
3399  bool ConstThis, bool VolatileThis) {
3400  assert(CanDeclareSpecialMemberFunction(RD) &&
3401  "doing special member lookup into record that isn't fully complete");
3402  RD = RD->getDefinition();
3403  if (RValueThis || ConstThis || VolatileThis)
3404  assert((SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::CopyAssignment ||
3405  SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::MoveAssignment) &&
3406  "constructors and destructors always have unqualified lvalue this");
3407  if (ConstArg || VolatileArg)
3408  assert((SM != CXXSpecialMemberKind::DefaultConstructor &&
3409  SM != CXXSpecialMemberKind::Destructor) &&
3410  "parameter-less special members can't have qualified arguments");
3411 
3412  // FIXME: Get the caller to pass in a location for the lookup.
3413  SourceLocation LookupLoc = RD->getLocation();
3414 
3415  llvm::FoldingSetNodeID ID;
3416  ID.AddPointer(RD);
3417  ID.AddInteger(llvm::to_underlying(SM));
3418  ID.AddInteger(ConstArg);
3419  ID.AddInteger(VolatileArg);
3420  ID.AddInteger(RValueThis);
3421  ID.AddInteger(ConstThis);
3422  ID.AddInteger(VolatileThis);
3423 
3424  void *InsertPoint;
3425  SpecialMemberOverloadResultEntry *Result =
3426  SpecialMemberCache.FindNodeOrInsertPos(ID, InsertPoint);
3427 
3428  // This was already cached
3429  if (Result)
3430  return *Result;
3431 
3432  Result = BumpAlloc.Allocate<SpecialMemberOverloadResultEntry>();
3433  Result = new (Result) SpecialMemberOverloadResultEntry(ID);
3434  SpecialMemberCache.InsertNode(Result, InsertPoint);
3435 
3436  if (SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::Destructor) {
3437  if (RD->needsImplicitDestructor()) {
3438  runWithSufficientStackSpace(RD->getLocation(), [&] {
3439  DeclareImplicitDestructor(RD);
3440  });
3441  }
3442  CXXDestructorDecl *DD = RD->getDestructor();
3443  Result->setMethod(DD);
3444  Result->setKind(DD && !DD->isDeleted()
3445  ? SpecialMemberOverloadResult::Success
3446  : SpecialMemberOverloadResult::NoMemberOrDeleted);
3447  return *Result;
3448  }
3449 
3450  // Prepare for overload resolution. Here we construct a synthetic argument
3451  // if necessary and make sure that implicit functions are declared.
3452  CanQualType CanTy = Context.getCanonicalType(Context.getTagDeclType(RD));
3453  DeclarationName Name;
3454  Expr *Arg = nullptr;
3455  unsigned NumArgs;
3456 
3457  QualType ArgType = CanTy;
3458  ExprValueKind VK = VK_LValue;
3459 
3460  if (SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::DefaultConstructor) {
3461  Name = Context.DeclarationNames.getCXXConstructorName(CanTy);
3462  NumArgs = 0;
3463  if (RD->needsImplicitDefaultConstructor()) {
3464  runWithSufficientStackSpace(RD->getLocation(), [&] {
3465  DeclareImplicitDefaultConstructor(RD);
3466  });
3467  }
3468  } else {
3469  if (SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::CopyConstructor ||
3470  SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::MoveConstructor) {
3471  Name = Context.DeclarationNames.getCXXConstructorName(CanTy);
3472  if (RD->needsImplicitCopyConstructor()) {
3473  runWithSufficientStackSpace(RD->getLocation(), [&] {
3474  DeclareImplicitCopyConstructor(RD);
3475  });
3476  }
3477  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 && RD->needsImplicitMoveConstructor()) {
3478  runWithSufficientStackSpace(RD->getLocation(), [&] {
3479  DeclareImplicitMoveConstructor(RD);
3480  });
3481  }
3482  } else {
3483  Name = Context.DeclarationNames.getCXXOperatorName(OO_Equal);
3484  if (RD->needsImplicitCopyAssignment()) {
3485  runWithSufficientStackSpace(RD->getLocation(), [&] {
3486  DeclareImplicitCopyAssignment(RD);
3487  });
3488  }
3489  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 && RD->needsImplicitMoveAssignment()) {
3490  runWithSufficientStackSpace(RD->getLocation(), [&] {
3491  DeclareImplicitMoveAssignment(RD);
3492  });
3493  }
3494  }
3495 
3496  if (ConstArg)
3497  ArgType.addConst();
3498  if (VolatileArg)
3499  ArgType.addVolatile();
3500 
3501  // This isn't /really/ specified by the standard, but it's implied
3502  // we should be working from a PRValue in the case of move to ensure
3503  // that we prefer to bind to rvalue references, and an LValue in the
3504  // case of copy to ensure we don't bind to rvalue references.
3505  // Possibly an XValue is actually correct in the case of move, but
3506  // there is no semantic difference for class types in this restricted
3507  // case.
3508  if (SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::CopyConstructor ||
3509  SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::CopyAssignment)
3510  VK = VK_LValue;
3511  else
3512  VK = VK_PRValue;
3513  }
3514 
3515  OpaqueValueExpr FakeArg(LookupLoc, ArgType, VK);
3516 
3517  if (SM != CXXSpecialMemberKind::DefaultConstructor) {
3518  NumArgs = 1;
3519  Arg = &FakeArg;
3520  }
3521 
3522  // Create the object argument
3523  QualType ThisTy = CanTy;
3524  if (ConstThis)
3525  ThisTy.addConst();
3526  if (VolatileThis)
3527  ThisTy.addVolatile();
3528  Expr::Classification Classification =
3529  OpaqueValueExpr(LookupLoc, ThisTy, RValueThis ? VK_PRValue : VK_LValue)
3530  .Classify(Context);
3531 
3532  // Now we perform lookup on the name we computed earlier and do overload
3533  // resolution. Lookup is only performed directly into the class since there
3534  // will always be a (possibly implicit) declaration to shadow any others.
3535  OverloadCandidateSet OCS(LookupLoc, OverloadCandidateSet::CSK_Normal);
3536  DeclContext::lookup_result R = RD->lookup(Name);
3537 
3538  if (R.empty()) {
3539  // We might have no default constructor because we have a lambda's closure
3540  // type, rather than because there's some other declared constructor.
3541  // Every class has a copy/move constructor, copy/move assignment, and
3542  // destructor.
3543  assert(SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::DefaultConstructor &&
3544  "lookup for a constructor or assignment operator was empty");
3545  Result->setMethod(nullptr);
3546  Result->setKind(SpecialMemberOverloadResult::NoMemberOrDeleted);
3547  return *Result;
3548  }
3549 
3550  // Copy the candidates as our processing of them may load new declarations
3551  // from an external source and invalidate lookup_result.
3552  SmallVector<NamedDecl *, 8> Candidates(R.begin(), R.end());
3553 
3554  for (NamedDecl *CandDecl : Candidates) {
3555  if (CandDecl->isInvalidDecl())
3556  continue;
3557 
3558  DeclAccessPair Cand = DeclAccessPair::make(CandDecl, AS_public);
3559  auto CtorInfo = getConstructorInfo(Cand);
3560  if (CXXMethodDecl *M = dyn_cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Cand->getUnderlyingDecl())) {
3561  if (SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::CopyAssignment ||
3562  SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::MoveAssignment)
3563  AddMethodCandidate(M, Cand, RD, ThisTy, Classification,
3564  llvm::ArrayRef(&Arg, NumArgs), OCS, true);
3565  else if (CtorInfo)
3566  AddOverloadCandidate(CtorInfo.Constructor, CtorInfo.FoundDecl,
3567  llvm::ArrayRef(&Arg, NumArgs), OCS,
3568  /*SuppressUserConversions*/ true);
3569  else
3570  AddOverloadCandidate(M, Cand, llvm::ArrayRef(&Arg, NumArgs), OCS,
3571  /*SuppressUserConversions*/ true);
3572  } else if (FunctionTemplateDecl *Tmpl =
3573  dyn_cast<FunctionTemplateDecl>(Cand->getUnderlyingDecl())) {
3574  if (SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::CopyAssignment ||
3575  SM == CXXSpecialMemberKind::MoveAssignment)
3576  AddMethodTemplateCandidate(Tmpl, Cand, RD, nullptr, ThisTy,
3577  Classification,
3578  llvm::ArrayRef(&Arg, NumArgs), OCS, true);
3579  else if (CtorInfo)
3580  AddTemplateOverloadCandidate(CtorInfo.ConstructorTmpl,
3581  CtorInfo.FoundDecl, nullptr,
3582  llvm::ArrayRef(&Arg, NumArgs), OCS, true);
3583  else
3584  AddTemplateOverloadCandidate(Tmpl, Cand, nullptr,
3585  llvm::ArrayRef(&Arg, NumArgs), OCS, true);
3586  } else {
3587  assert(isa<UsingDecl>(Cand.getDecl()) &&
3588  "illegal Kind of operator = Decl");
3589  }
3590  }
3591 
3592  OverloadCandidateSet::iterator Best;
3593  switch (OCS.BestViableFunction(*this, LookupLoc, Best)) {
3594  case OR_Success:
3595  Result->setMethod(cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Best->Function));
3596  Result->setKind(SpecialMemberOverloadResult::Success);
3597  break;
3598 
3599  case OR_Deleted:
3600  Result->setMethod(cast<CXXMethodDecl>(Best->Function));
3601  Result->setKind(SpecialMemberOverloadResult::NoMemberOrDeleted);
3602  break;
3603 
3604  case OR_Ambiguous:
3605  Result->setMethod(nullptr);
3606  Result->setKind(SpecialMemberOverloadResult::Ambiguous);
3607  break;
3608 
3609  case OR_No_Viable_Function:
3610  Result->setMethod(nullptr);
3611  Result->setKind(SpecialMemberOverloadResult::NoMemberOrDeleted);
3612  break;
3613  }
3614 
3615  return *Result;
3616 }
3617

3622  false, false, false, false, false);

3649 /// Look up the constructors for the given class.
3650 DeclContext::lookup_result Sema::LookupConstructors(CXXRecordDecl *Class) {
3651  // If the implicit constructors have not yet been declared, do so now.
3652  if (CanDeclareSpecialMemberFunction(Class)) {
3653  runWithSufficientStackSpace(Class->getLocation(), [&] {
3654  if (Class->needsImplicitDefaultConstructor())
3655  DeclareImplicitDefaultConstructor(Class);
3656  if (Class->needsImplicitCopyConstructor())
3657  DeclareImplicitCopyConstructor(Class);

3661  }

3664  DeclarationName Name = Context.DeclarationNames.getCXXConstructorName(T);
3665  return Class->lookup(Name);

3712 /// LookupLiteralOperator - Determine which literal operator should be used for
3713 /// a user-defined literal, per C++11 [lex.ext].
3714 ///
3715 /// Normal overload resolution is not used to select which literal operator to
3716 /// call for a user-defined literal. Look up the provided literal operator name,
3717 /// and filter the results to the appropriate set for the given argument types.
3718 Sema::LiteralOperatorLookupResult
3719 Sema::LookupLiteralOperator(Scope *S, LookupResult &R,
3720  ArrayRef<QualType> ArgTys, bool AllowRaw,
3721  bool AllowTemplate, bool AllowStringTemplatePack,
3722  bool DiagnoseMissing, StringLiteral *StringLit) {
3723  LookupName(R, S);
3724  assert(R.getResultKind() != LookupResult::Ambiguous &&
3725  "literal operator lookup can't be ambiguous");
3726 
3727  // Filter the lookup results appropriately.
3728  LookupResult::Filter F = R.makeFilter();
3729 
3730  bool AllowCooked = true;
3731  bool FoundRaw = false;
3732  bool FoundTemplate = false;
3733  bool FoundStringTemplatePack = false;
3734  bool FoundCooked = false;
3735 
3736  while (F.hasNext()) {
3737  Decl *D = F.next();
3738  if (UsingShadowDecl *USD = dyn_cast<UsingShadowDecl>(D))
3739  D = USD->getTargetDecl();
3740 
3741  // If the declaration we found is invalid, skip it.
3742  if (D->isInvalidDecl()) {
3743  F.erase();
3744  continue;
3745  }
3746 
3747  bool IsRaw = false;
3748  bool IsTemplate = false;
3749  bool IsStringTemplatePack = false;
3750  bool IsCooked = false;
3751 
3752  if (FunctionDecl *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionDecl>(D)) {
3753  if (FD->getNumParams() == 1 &&
3754  FD->getParamDecl(0)->getType()->getAs<PointerType>())
3755  IsRaw = true;
3756  else if (FD->getNumParams() == ArgTys.size()) {
3757  IsCooked = true;
3758  for (unsigned ArgIdx = 0; ArgIdx != ArgTys.size(); ++ArgIdx) {
3759  QualType ParamTy = FD->getParamDecl(ArgIdx)->getType();
3760  if (!Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ArgTys[ArgIdx], ParamTy)) {
3761  IsCooked = false;
3762  break;
3763  }
3764  }
3765  }
3766  }
3767  if (FunctionTemplateDecl *FD = dyn_cast<FunctionTemplateDecl>(D)) {
3768  TemplateParameterList *Params = FD->getTemplateParameters();
3769  if (Params->size() == 1) {
3770  IsTemplate = true;
3771  if (!Params->getParam(0)->isTemplateParameterPack() && !StringLit) {
3772  // Implied but not stated: user-defined integer and floating literals
3773  // only ever use numeric literal operator templates, not templates
3774  // taking a parameter of class type.
3775  F.erase();
3776  continue;
3777  }
3778 
3779  // A string literal template is only considered if the string literal
3780  // is a well-formed template argument for the template parameter.
3781  if (StringLit) {
3782  SFINAETrap Trap(*this);
3783  SmallVector<TemplateArgument, 1> SugaredChecked, CanonicalChecked;
3784  TemplateArgumentLoc Arg(TemplateArgument(StringLit), StringLit);
3785  if (CheckTemplateArgument(
3786  Params->getParam(0), Arg, FD, R.getNameLoc(), R.getNameLoc(),
3787  0, SugaredChecked, CanonicalChecked, CTAK_Specified) ||
3788  Trap.hasErrorOccurred())
3789  IsTemplate = false;
3790  }
3791  } else {
3792  IsStringTemplatePack = true;
3793  }
3794  }
3795 
3796  if (AllowTemplate && StringLit && IsTemplate) {
3797  FoundTemplate = true;
3798  AllowRaw = false;
3799  AllowCooked = false;
3800  AllowStringTemplatePack = false;
3801  if (FoundRaw || FoundCooked || FoundStringTemplatePack) {
3802  F.restart();
3803  FoundRaw = FoundCooked = FoundStringTemplatePack = false;
3804  }
3805  } else if (AllowCooked && IsCooked) {
3806  FoundCooked = true;
3807  AllowRaw = false;
3808  AllowTemplate = StringLit;
3809  AllowStringTemplatePack = false;
3810  if (FoundRaw || FoundTemplate || FoundStringTemplatePack) {
3811  // Go through again and remove the raw and template decls we've
3812  // already found.
3813  F.restart();
3814  FoundRaw = FoundTemplate = FoundStringTemplatePack = false;
3815  }
3816  } else if (AllowRaw && IsRaw) {
3817  FoundRaw = true;
3818  } else if (AllowTemplate && IsTemplate) {
3819  FoundTemplate = true;
3820  } else if (AllowStringTemplatePack && IsStringTemplatePack) {
3821  FoundStringTemplatePack = true;
3822  } else {
3823  F.erase();
3824  }
3825  }
3826 
3827  F.done();
3828 
3829  // Per C++20 [lex.ext]p5, we prefer the template form over the non-template
3830  // form for string literal operator templates.
3831  if (StringLit && FoundTemplate)
3832  return LOLR_Template;
3833 
3834  // C++11 [lex.ext]p3, p4: If S contains a literal operator with a matching
3835  // parameter type, that is used in preference to a raw literal operator
3836  // or literal operator template.
3837  if (FoundCooked)
3838  return LOLR_Cooked;
3839 
3840  // C++11 [lex.ext]p3, p4: S shall contain a raw literal operator or a literal
3841  // operator template, but not both.
3842  if (FoundRaw && FoundTemplate) {
3843  Diag(R.getNameLoc(), diag::err_ovl_ambiguous_call) << R.getLookupName();
3844  for (const NamedDecl *D : R)
3845  NoteOverloadCandidate(D, D->getUnderlyingDecl()->getAsFunction());
3846  return LOLR_Error;
3847  }
3848 
3849  if (FoundRaw)
3850  return LOLR_Raw;
3851 
3852  if (FoundTemplate)
3853  return LOLR_Template;
3854 
3855  if (FoundStringTemplatePack)
3856  return LOLR_StringTemplatePack;
3857 
3858  // Didn't find anything we could use.
3859  if (DiagnoseMissing) {
3860  Diag(R.getNameLoc(), diag::err_ovl_no_viable_literal_operator)
3861  << R.getLookupName() << (int)ArgTys.size() << ArgTys[0]
3862  << (ArgTys.size() == 2 ? ArgTys[1] : QualType()) << AllowRaw
3863  << (AllowTemplate || AllowStringTemplatePack);
3864  return LOLR_Error;
3865  }
3866 
3867  return LOLR_ErrorNoDiagnostic;
3868 }
3869 
3870 void ADLResult::insert(NamedDecl *New) {
3871  NamedDecl *&Old = Decls[cast<NamedDecl>(New->getCanonicalDecl())];
3872 
3873  // If we haven't yet seen a decl for this key, or the last decl
3874  // was exactly this one, we're done.
3875  if (Old == nullptr || Old == New) {
3876  Old = New;
3877  return;
3878  }
3879 
3880  // Otherwise, decide which is a more recent redeclaration.
3881  FunctionDecl *OldFD = Old->getAsFunction();
3882  FunctionDecl *NewFD = New->getAsFunction();
3883 
3884  FunctionDecl *Cursor = NewFD;
3885  while (true) {
3886  Cursor = Cursor->getPreviousDecl();
3887 
3888  // If we got to the end without finding OldFD, OldFD is the newer
3889  // declaration; leave things as they are.
3890  if (!Cursor) return;
3891 
3892  // If we do find OldFD, then NewFD is newer.
3893  if (Cursor == OldFD) break;
3894 
3895  // Otherwise, keep looking.
3896  }
3897 
3898  Old = New;
3899 }
3900 
3901 void Sema::ArgumentDependentLookup(DeclarationName Name, SourceLocation Loc,
3902  ArrayRef<Expr *> Args, ADLResult &Result) {
3903  // Find all of the associated namespaces and classes based on the
3904  // arguments we have.
3905  AssociatedNamespaceSet AssociatedNamespaces;
3906  AssociatedClassSet AssociatedClasses;
3907  FindAssociatedClassesAndNamespaces(Loc, Args,
3908  AssociatedNamespaces,
3909  AssociatedClasses);
3910 
3911  // C++ [basic.lookup.argdep]p3:
3912  // Let X be the lookup set produced by unqualified lookup (3.4.1)
3913  // and let Y be the lookup set produced by argument dependent
3914  // lookup (defined as follows). If X contains [...] then Y is
3915  // empty. Otherwise Y is the set of declarations found in the
3916  // namespaces associated with the argument types as described
3917  // below. The set of declarations found by the lookup of the name
3918  // is the union of X and Y.
3919  //
3920  // Here, we compute Y and add its members to the overloaded
3921  // candidate set.
3922  for (auto *NS : AssociatedNamespaces) {
3923  // When considering an associated namespace, the lookup is the
3924  // same as the lookup performed when the associated namespace is
3925  // used as a qualifier (3.4.3.2) except that:
3926  //
3927  // -- Any using-directives in the associated namespace are
3928  // ignored.
3929  //
3930  // -- Any namespace-scope friend functions declared in
3931  // associated classes are visible within their respective
3932  // namespaces even if they are not visible during an ordinary
3933  // lookup (11.4).
3934  //
3935  // C++20 [basic.lookup.argdep] p4.3
3936  // -- are exported, are attached to a named module M, do not appear
3937  // in the translation unit containing the point of the lookup, and
3938  // have the same innermost enclosing non-inline namespace scope as
3939  // a declaration of an associated entity attached to M.
3940  DeclContext::lookup_result R = NS->lookup(Name);
3941  for (auto *D : R) {
3942  auto *Underlying = D;
3943  if (auto *USD = dyn_cast<UsingShadowDecl>(D))
3944  Underlying = USD->getTargetDecl();
3945 
3946  if (!isa<FunctionDecl>(Underlying) &&
3947  !isa<FunctionTemplateDecl>(Underlying))
3948  continue;
3949 
3950  // The declaration is visible to argument-dependent lookup if either
3951  // it's ordinarily visible or declared as a friend in an associated
3952  // class.
3953  bool Visible = false;
3954  for (D = D->getMostRecentDecl(); D;
3955  D = cast_or_null<NamedDecl>(D->getPreviousDecl())) {
3956  if (D->getIdentifierNamespace() & Decl::IDNS_Ordinary) {
3957  if (isVisible(D)) {
3958  Visible = true;
3959  break;
3960  }
3961 
3962  if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlusModules)
3963  continue;
3964 
3965  if (D->isInExportDeclContext()) {
3966  Module *FM = D->getOwningModule();
3967  // C++20 [basic.lookup.argdep] p4.3 .. are exported ...
3968  // exports are only valid in module purview and outside of any
3969  // PMF (although a PMF should not even be present in a module
3970  // with an import).
3971  assert(FM && FM->isNamedModule() && !FM->isPrivateModule() &&
3972  "bad export context");
3973  // .. are attached to a named module M, do not appear in the
3974  // translation unit containing the point of the lookup..
3975  if (D->isInAnotherModuleUnit() &&
3976  llvm::any_of(AssociatedClasses, [&](auto *E) {
3977  // ... and have the same innermost enclosing non-inline
3978  // namespace scope as a declaration of an associated entity
3979  // attached to M
3980  if (E->getOwningModule() != FM)
3981  return false;
3982  // TODO: maybe this could be cached when generating the
3983  // associated namespaces / entities.
3984  DeclContext *Ctx = E->getDeclContext();
3985  while (!Ctx->isFileContext() || Ctx->isInlineNamespace())
3986  Ctx = Ctx->getParent();
3987  return Ctx == NS;
3988  })) {
3989  Visible = true;
3990  break;
3991  }
3992  }
3993  } else if (D->getFriendObjectKind()) {
3994  auto *RD = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(D->getLexicalDeclContext());
3995  // [basic.lookup.argdep]p4:
3996  // Argument-dependent lookup finds all declarations of functions and
3997  // function templates that
3998  // - ...
3999  // - are declared as a friend ([class.friend]) of any class with a
4000  // reachable definition in the set of associated entities,
4001  //
4002  // FIXME: If there's a merged definition of D that is reachable, then
4003  // the friend declaration should be considered.
4004  if (AssociatedClasses.count(RD) && isReachable(D)) {
4005  Visible = true;
4006  break;
4007  }
4008  }
4009  }
4010 
4011  // FIXME: Preserve D as the FoundDecl.
4012  if (Visible)
4013  Result.insert(Underlying);
4014  }
4015  }
4016 }

4018 //----------------------------------------------------------------------------
4019 // Search for all visible declarations.

4021 VisibleDeclConsumer::~VisibleDeclConsumer() { }

4023 bool VisibleDeclConsumer::includeHiddenDecls() const { return false; }
